issues: Page title and H1 do not align - title emphasizes 'Low Vision Support Organization' while H1 is generic 'Welcome to Vision-Aid'
Title contains formatting issue: '#1Low' appears to have a stray '#1' character that should be removed
H1 is vague and generic - 'Welcome to' doesn't describe page purpose or content
Title relies on organizational context rather than describing what users will find on the page
1. Page Title.improved_example: Vision Aid: Low Vision Support Organization - Resources & Services | Vision-Aid

vague_headings: Any gift of Smart Assistive Technology will be doubled by a generous matching grant.
Note:- Email is the preferred and recommended way to contact us.
issues: Multiple H1 headings present (should be only one per page) - 'Welcome to Vision-Aid' appears 5 times
Duplicate H2 heading 'Welcome to Vision-Aid!' appears multiple times at the start of sections
Entire heading structure repeats 5 times identically - suggests page content is duplicated or poorly templated
H3 'What's New' appears after H1 without intermediate H2 - illogical nesting
H2 'Highlights from the last quarter' appears 5 times - excessive repetition without clear differentiation
Many H2 headings are individual story titles (Farhan, Monika, etc.) that should likely be H3 under a parent section
H2 'Any gift of Smart Assistive Technology will be doubled by a generous matching grant.' is a sentence, not a heading - should be body text
H2 'Note:- Email is the preferred and recommended way to contact us.' is instructional text, not a section heading

issues.description: Found 44 nav landmarks. This is excessive and creates cognitive overload for assistive technology users.
issues.recommendation: Consolidate navigation elements. Multiple nav landmarks should only be used when they serve distinct purposes (e.g., main navigation vs. breadcrumbs). Consider using aria-label to differentiate them.

issues.description: Found 10 search landmarks. Multiple search regions are excessive and confusing.
issues.recommendation: Typically only one search landmark is needed per page. Remove duplicates or consolidate search functionality.

issues.description: Found 4 main landmarks. Only one main landmark should exist per page.
issues.recommendation: Remove duplicate main landmarks. There should be exactly one <main> element per page.

issues.description: Found 4 footer landmarks. Multiple footers are unusual and likely indicate structural duplication.
issues.recommendation: Consolidate footer content. Typically only one footer per page is appropriate.

issues.description: Multiple nav landmarks lack aria-labels (16 unlabeled nav elements). When multiple nav landmarks exist, each must be uniquely labeled.
issues.recommendation: Add descriptive aria-labels to all nav elements (e.g., 'Main navigation', 'Footer navigation', 'Sidebar navigation').
Add aria-labels to search landmarks to distinguish their purpose if multiple are necessary.

issues.description: Page structure appears to be duplicated multiple times (nav-main-footer patterns repeat 4 times), suggesting possible template rendering errors or unintended page duplication.
issues.recommendation: Review page structure for unintended duplication. Ensure landmarks appear only once per logical page section.

high_priority_issues: Excessive empty alt text on images (130+ images with empty alt attributes) - Critical for screen reader users, especially problematic for an organization serving visually impaired individuals
Severe heading hierarchy violations - Multiple H1 tags (5+), H3 tags appearing before H2 tags, and inconsistent nesting patterns that break document structure for assistive technology users
Massive content duplication - Entire page content repeated 4-5 times, creating navigation confusion and inflated page size for users with assistive technologies
Links without accessible names - 80+ links missing text or aria-labels, including social media icons and navigation elements that are inaccessible to screen reader users
Missing form labels and aria-labels - Multiple form fields lack proper ARIA labeling, making them difficult or impossible to identify for assistive technology users
moderate_issues: Page title mismatch - Title contains '#1Low Vision Support Organization' (appears concatenated) while H1 is 'Welcome to Vision-Aid', creating confusion about page purpose
Inconsistent landmark usage - Multiple unlabeled nav and search regions; some navigation landmarks lack aria-labels for distinction
Typos in content - 'signle' instead of 'single', 'Univeristy' instead of 'University', 'An short film' instead of 'A short film' - impacts readability for users with cognitive disabilities
Iframe accessibility - While iframes have titles, they lack descriptions of interactive content within them
Redundant form instances - Multiple identical search and subscription forms repeated throughout page without clear purpose differentiation
low_priority_issues: Button text inconsistency - Some buttons have only aria-labels without visible text (carousel controls)
Subscribe button missing aria-label - Single button without aria-label among otherwise labeled buttons
Minor semantic issues - Some headings used as decorative elements rather than structural markers (e.g., 'For more details click here' as H2)
Potential color contrast issues - Not directly visible in semantic data but should be verified given organization's focus on low vision support

high_priority_issues: CRITICAL: 41% of actionable images (202/494) lack alt text entirely — these are images inside links and buttons with no accessible name. Users cannot identify link destinations.
CRITICAL: Search icon (fas fa-search) is sole content of interactive element with aria-hidden=true and no accessible name — search functionality is completely inaccessible.
CRITICAL: All 5 SVGs lack any accessibility attributes (role, aria-label, aria-labelledby, title, desc) — completely inaccessible to screen readers.
CRITICAL: 30% of informative images (18/60) have vague or generic alt text ('A girl', 'A boy', 'collage', 'Group of People') that fails to convey meaningful information.
CRITICAL: Logo images used as links lack aria-label — link purpose is unclear to assistive technology users.
moderate_issues: WCAG 1.1.1 (Level A): 202 actionable images with null alt text violate basic alt text requirement for images in interactive contexts.
WCAG 1.1.1 (Level A): Vague alt text on 18 informative images ('A girl', 'A boy') provides minimal context — should include identifying details or context.
WCAG 4.1.2 (Level A): Icon fonts with aria-hidden=true but no sibling text (chevron-left, chevron-right, building, envelope, phone, home, facebook-square) lack accessible names.
WCAG 1.1.1 (Level A): 1 actionable image (nidhi.jpg) lacks alt text despite being inside a link to 'Sitapur Eye Hospital'.
Massive content duplication: 564 total images with 60 unique informative images repeated 5-6 times across pages — suggests template/carousel reuse without proper alt text management.
WCAG 1.1.1 (Level A): Decorative images (Shakuntala poster, VisionAid Banner) correctly have null alt, but lack explicit role='presentation' or aria-hidden for clarity.
low_priority_issues: WCAG 1.1.1 (Level A): One image alt text contains possessive apostrophe ('Mohan Raj's', 'Anshu's') — minor but inconsistent formatting.
WCAG 1.1.1 (Level A): Alt text 'beneficiary-undergoing-vision-check--scaled' includes filename artifact ('--scaled') — should be descriptive only.
Icon font caret-down has aria-hidden=false but no aria-label — unclear if intentional or oversight.
SVG elements present but completely undocumented — no indication of whether they are decorative or informative.
patterns_observed: Pattern 1: Massive duplication — 60 unique images repeated 5-6 times (564 total). Suggests multi-page site or carousel with copy-paste implementation. All duplicates inherit same alt text issues.
Pattern 2: Actionable images systematically lack alt text — 41% of links/buttons with images have no accessible name. This is a structural problem, not isolated instances.

Pattern 3: Vague alt text on people images — 30% use generic descriptors ('A girl', 'A boy', 'A man') instead of names or context. Particularly problematic for testimonial/team photos where identity matters.

Pattern 4: Icon fonts inconsistently handled — Social media icons (Facebook, Twitter, YouTube) are aria-hidden with sibling text (acceptable), but search icon is aria-hidden with NO sibling text (critical failure).
Pattern 5: SVGs completely inaccessible — All 5 SVGs lack any semantic markup. No role, aria-label, title, or desc elements. Likely decorative but undocumented.
Pattern 6: Logo reuse without context — VisionAid logo appears 20+ times as link with same alt text but no aria-label on link itself. Link purpose unclear.
Pattern 7: Map images in buttons have good alt text ('Map of India', 'Map of USA') with aria-label on buttons — these are done correctly and should be model for other actionable images.
8. Overall Summary.score_rationale: Score reflects: (1) 41% of actionable images missing alt text entirely (critical); (2) All 5 SVGs completely inaccessible (critical); (3) Search icon sole content with no accessible name (critical); (4) 30% of informative images with vague alt text (major); (5) Massive duplication amplifying issues across 564 images; (6) Some correct implementations (decorative images, map buttons) prevent score from being lower. Positive: 100% of decorative images correctly null-alt'd; social media icons have sibling text fallback. Negative: Structural problems with actionable images and SVGs indicate systemic accessibility gaps rather than isolated oversights.
